2: Single Point of Failure: Eliminating the Achilles' Heel
â¡ï¸ What is it? A system design where a single component failure can bring the entire system down, leading to data loss and service disruption.ğŸ’¥
â¡ï¸ Why is it problematic? Centralized systems with a single point of failure are highly vulnerable to:ğŸš¨
â†’ Hardware failures: Server crashes, disk failures, or power outages can render the entire system inaccessible.
â†’ Software bugs: A critical bug in the central server software can lead to system-wide issues.ğŸ’¥
â¡ï¸ Solution: Embrace distributed data storage
â†’ Distribute data copies across multiple geographically dispersed servers.ğŸŒ
â†’ If one server fails, others can continue serving requests and maintaining system availability.ğŸ› ï¸

#singlepointoffailure #systemdesign #datalossprevention

3: Vertical Scaling: Hitting the Ceiling
â¡ï¸ What is it? Upgrading the hardware capacity of a single server to handle increased workload and data demands.ğŸ“ˆ
â¡ï¸ Limitations:
â†’ Cost-ineffective: Continuously upgrading hardware can become expensive and impractical as the system scales.ğŸ’°
â†’ Performance bottlenecks: Even with powerful hardware, single servers can reach limitations in processing power and I/O capabilities.ğŸš«
â¡ï¸ Solution: Embrace horizontal scaling
â†’ Add more servers to the distributed system to share the workload and data storage.â•
â†’ This approach offers greater scalability and cost-effectiveness as additional resources can be easily added as needed.ğŸ”„

#verticaldcaling #hardwareupgrades #scalability

4: Latency Issues: Bridging the Distance Gap
â¡ï¸ What is it? The time it takes for data to travel between different locations, impacting user experience and system performance.â³
â¡ï¸ Challenges:
â†’ Geographical dispersion: Users accessing data from distant locations experience higher latency due to longer network distances.ğŸŒ
â†’ Centralized data storage: Storing data in a single location can lead to increased latency for geographically distant users.ğŸ¯
â¡ï¸ Solution: Distribute data geographically
â†’ Replicate data across servers located in different regions closer to user populations.ğŸ—ºï¸
â†’ This reduces the distance data needs to travel, minimizing latency and improving user experience.ğŸš€

#latencyissues #datatraveltime #userexperience

5: Distributed Data Storage: A Balancing Act
â¡ï¸ Benefits:
â†’ Improved reliability: Eliminates single points of failure and ensures data availability even during server outages.ğŸ›¡ï¸
â†’ Enhanced performance: Reduces latency for geographically diverse users by bringing data closer to them.ğŸï¸
â†’ Increased scalability: Enables horizontal scaling by adding more servers to the distributed system.ğŸ“ˆ
â¡ï¸ Challenges:
â†’ Maintaining consistency: Ensuring all data replicas across different servers remain consistent requires careful design and protocols.ğŸ”’
â†’ Increased complexity: Managing and coordinating data across multiple servers adds complexity to the system.ğŸ¤¯

